{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"52f3a32f-47df-4fde-9290-6fb457ece01c","content":"For waits/blocks under load, collect a **Thread Time (wall-clock) trace** with PerfView. This captures both on-CPU and off-CPU time (locks, I/O, async awaits).\n\n**PerfView command:**\n\n```cmd\nPerfView /ThreadTime /GCCollectOnly /NoGui /AcceptEULA /MaxCollectSec:30 collect\n```\n\nKey flags:\n| Flag | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `/ThreadTime` | Enables context-switch & CPU-sample events so you see **where threads are waiting** |\n| `/GCCollectOnly` | Keeps GC detail but avoids noisy allocation events |\n| `/MaxCollectSec:30` | Auto-stops after 30 s (adjust to your repro window) |\n| `/NoGui` | Headless — good for servers |\n\n**After collection**, open the `.etl` file and use the **Thread Time Stacks** view, filter to your process, and look at `BLOCKED_TIME` and `AWAIT_TIME` nodes to find contention points.\n\n> **Tip:** If you suspect async stalls specifically, also add `/ClrEvents:GC+Contention+Exception` to capture lock-contention events alongside thread-time data.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d849b2ae-a72d-4ee3-8fea-51ef788fde86","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about performance tracing for an ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) app on Windows Server with slow requests under load. They want to know which trace to collect and what PerfView arguments to use. This is a knowledge/advisory question, not a code task.","outputTokens":373},"id":"0f3c6e31-779b-4800-bf73-b543c872657c","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:44:12.635Z","parentId":"4bb8a67f-2b79-4d81-9064-16cc8dad2d13"}
